text: Do you know of any male APNs in the workforce? Yes. Okay, then would you agree that there are very few male APNs in the workforce? I think it's in comparison with the nursing population. Like if it's 110, then it will probably be 110 to the nursing population as well for APNs as well. Okay, maybe let me share some statistics with you. So, currently in Singapore we have about 11% of the RN population that are men. But for our APN workforce, only about 5.something% are males. So why do you think there is such an under-representation of men in the APN workforce? So, I cannot represent my view for all, but I think somehow male nurses tend to go towards the administrative part of the role. So maybe that could be one reason why we chose a lesser representative of male nurses that want to be an APN. Where we know that for APN, they would rather want to pursue on the clinical pathway. So that could be one reason. Another reason that I could think of would be administrative. I'm just thinking about all the male nurses that I have in my hospital. Either administrative or more towards skilled day type of work. So they may go into orthopedic perhaps. And then I think for APN itself, the beneficial ones are actually more so on the medical discipline. So that could be another second reason. But I really didn't really ask too many. But to me, male and female are no different. But if you are really interested in the clinical pathway and you want to pursue the APN path, then I think it shouldn't be limited to whether it should be male or female. As long as you are capable and have that passion to go into clinical pathway, especially like APN. So you were talking about administrative roles. What are the administrative roles you are thinking of? So it would be like nurse manager. I have quite a few quite bright male nurses who go into more of strategic planning, planning type of work. So it's more of those type of work rather than going to the clinical pathway. Why do you think that men are more inclined to go and do more administrative sort of work compared to APN kind of work? I guess it would be their interest, right? I cannot doubt that there are male nurses who are really very caring as well and who like to pursue the clinical pathway. But there are some who are really, in terms of their mind, they are more methodical. Like more logistically can plan things. Or even better in writing of corporate complications. Because I have got a few very talented ones which are really inclined in those rather than... Or they may even go to research. But quite a few male nurses who actually chose to do that. Quite a few compared to female nurses. So it seems like they are more towards the other pathway. And I thought all of them are equally as good. Let's say if they have decided to choose the clinical pathway as well. In the end, ultimately it goes back to their interest. What do they want to succeed in within the three pathways? Administrative, clinical, education and research. I'm trying to also say that in the clinical track where there is the nurse clinicians and all that. Men tend not to choose that track as well? So my male nurse clinicians... I look after both advanced practitioners and specialty care nurses. So basically my specialty nurses who are male mainly go into the wound care. And then they will go to orthopaedic. So more skill-based work. For example, maybe they really like the hands-on type of stuff. Rather than the counselling and education. Whereas the rest of the education, counselling or other specialty would be held by the female nurses. I see. Then do you think that it is important to have more men in the APN workforce? I think whether it is male or female, it is important. Must be passionate. Must be able to endure the APN journey. And they must have a correct mindset that when they come into APN, they are into clinical work, service, running like the inpatient or outpatient. It is not to go into APN because they want to climb up the career ladder. Like to be promoted or stuff. So they must really have that passion. So be it male or female, to me that's the most important thing. So you don't think that having more men in the APN workforce will make much difference at all? It's more of the character of the candidate. I guess there needs to be a good mix. Because I think there are some ways where guys think a little bit different. I mean male thinks a little bit different from female. So I appreciate how you can work together. It doesn't need to have like... I think in the workforce itself, I think we appreciate the way how different people think. And that is how a team is formed. And I think a team that is formed cannot be of the same character or same personality or the same way of thinking. Because you will not have change. You will not have how to improve things. So I appreciate that there is a good mix of male and female or different type of people. So what is the difference between men and women that make you think that you will bring a good mix? Again? Repeat your question please. What is the difference between male and female nurses that will bring a good mix into the APN workforce? Because you speak a lot about there is a good mix. You cannot have people of the same type. So what is the difference between men and women? I think men tend... Actually there are also different type of males. So we have those males who are like body leader type. Then they would be able to throw ideas, give a plan thing, or write in a way that maybe different from how others may. But that doesn't discount that some of the females are not able to do so. So probably it's really... Perhaps what I appreciate about the male nurses is that although they are not like the motherly kind of looking after the other nurses, they can be like the authoritative type that actually also keep their colleagues in check as well. And making sure that they are looked after. And if they need to speak up, they may be the ones that speak up for it. But actually all my male nurses are okay. Really very good. We appreciate them for who they are. But yeah, we really appreciate them for who they are. But if they want to join APN, I can say my existing nurse function may not want to. Because they are already in their area of expectation for very very long and they don't think that they need to go into the APN. Then that would be their reason why they continue to choose their career path as a nurse clinician. So specifically to the APN group, I mean your APN colleagues, I understand that in your institution you don't have any male APNs yet. So how do you think that having men amongst your APN colleagues would change the dynamics of things? Okay, so currently I am one from another hospital who is a male APN who nested to one of my departments, following one of my APNs. Actually I don't really see a difference whether it is male or female. I think whatever it is, he just needs to do the necessary work and get all the learning in place so that he can function as an APN. I'm really not too sure what other things the male APN can bring to work, like the career or even my department. I feel it is not, we shouldn't finger them out because they are male or female. I think it really depends on whether they have that, in Chinese it's called 听和力, like they have that commitment, that passion to be able to bring across the APN. So it doesn't need to be male or female because I've got very good female ones who are able to do so as well. That's a very good point. Even during interviews, because what my hospital does is that we have two rounds of interviews when we are interviewing for APNs to go for the master's program because the male APN was never one of the factors, but more so their experience. The clinical experience that they have been working, what is the intended specialty they are going to specialise in, actually plays a much important role because if let's say they chose a specialty that perhaps the hospital doesn't specialise in that they need for that service, then they may need to switch to other specialty as well. So it will be based on what the hospital requirements are, what we think the service is needed so that we will grow the APN with that specialty. Rather than whether this person is a male or female. You were talking about the recruitment procedure for your institution, maybe you can share your experience of being recruited yourself. How did you first get recruited into the MN program? During my time, it was less stringent. When I was first approached by one of my assistant directors, Dan, she just asked whether I was interested in clinical nursing, whether I was interested to further my studies, which I was then very passionate about, rather than doing the administrative role. The minute they offered the opportunity that I would like to go for it, I went for it and I just had an interview from the NUS who subsequently got into APN. Whereas now it is much more stringent, it's much more harder. It's not about my choice whether the nurse wants to upgrade the studies and wants to do the part-time work. But rather, again, like what we mentioned just now, we look at what are the specialties that this person is interested to be in, what is the clinical experience of this person, and then we will ask a series of questions to find out whether this person actually is suitable for the APN. Some people may not even come in thinking what the career is going to be like. So we really want to preempt them to go and find out from other APNs what is the work that they are going to do in the future, not just because I am an APN, I can start ordering a doctor around or I can prescribe medicine or I can tell the doctor what diseases need to be done. I think it is more than that. You probably really want to know how to manage a certain group of patients and you are safe or in fact actually the CUs that have that potential to want to choose APNs as their career path. From there, that is about their aptitude, their personality. Then subsequently, if they pass that round of panel interview, that panel interview will include APNs like myself, the HR people and also the nurse education people. Then we will ask them a few questions and then we went through this panel interview, then they will go through another round of, we call it the MMI, multiple mini interviews where we look into how they critically think in clinical situations, just like the mini or C but at an S&M level, so that we see how is their clinical acuteness is like and how will they respond to those questions. If they pass through these two, then we will tell them that okay, then you are selected to go for the Master's of Medicine. We have to be very, very careful about the way we choose our APNs because it is like a HDD flag that if you have to back pay, the bond is like saying don't back pay. So we must make sure that the person that we choose, whether it's a male or female, will succeed in this APN pathway. That will be our financial. Is there any reason why there is a representative from the nursing education sitting in the first round of interviews? So they are the ones who need the sponsorship. So they will also give feedback about this person, whether their previous academic requirements. So we also want to make sure the person that we send can pass the Master's of Medicine. Let's say for example, this person is more of a field-based or more doing one, then they should still meet the academic part of the requirement. So that is where our nurse education colleagues also come in to do some work. Seems like a lot of things are being covered during the interview and also the recruitment process and nomination process. I'm just wondering, do nursing leaders take into consideration the gender of the RN when nominating him or her for the MN programme? I don't think so. I think when the nurse manager or the nurse clinician nominates, they think probably that the nurses, whether male or female, perhaps because they want to go into this pathway. Because they do know that it is a one and a half year course, another one year internship, then after that it becomes a three year course. Some may consider all these factors before they put up the application. I'm sure their ward sisters or brother would have also advised them accordingly to tell them what do they see them as. Do they think that they really deserve a foot for the clinical path? But definitely they won't be able to get all the information from the ward sisters or ward brothers. Because probably when they come to the panel interview, we will give them all the information that they need. During the interview, maybe we talk about your time first, rather than now. For yourself, when you were being recruited and your nursing leader spoke to you about entering this course and also to pursue this track, was there any adjustments that you had to make for your personal life? Because in terms of family planning, because I understand you're married, did you have to make some adjustments at that point of time? At that point of time, I was much younger, I wasn't married yet. So I just thought, because I was in 7th year of my nursing, and then they offered me the option of pursuing my Master of Programming, of course you get that opportunity. So I think for some, the only probably limiting factor would be, a lot of times they say if you go for your studies, your promotion will be held up. Meaning that because basically to the organisation, you go to school, you study, you are not actually contributing to the hospital. And then that is where your, for example, your performance appraisal, your salary bonus, all this, may be at the normal group rate. You cannot expect a higher pay or anything like that when you go to study. And even your promotion may be pulled back later after your internship. Because during your internship, they will also be near you at your field learning. So you are not contributing to the hospital, and then they will still not promote you. But until you reach to the, you pass your APM, you start some service, and you prove some value from the work that you do, then they may have promotion. But otherwise, like personal-wise, because at that point of time, I think I wasn't into faculty yet, so it doesn't really affect me that much. But I know of my classmates who are married, and at that point of time, they may be having children, so it may be tough for them because it's hard. So the thing that we hear about from our classmates is that, oh, my children don't recognise me anymore because mummy don't have time to look after them because they have to study. So these are probably what my classmates have shared with me. But I also have quite a lot of classmates that got pregnant and have children. So I think both ways, I guess. So that was during your time, quite a number of years ago, right? But how about now? When you speak with potential candidates, do you explore this area with them? Yeah, during the panel interview, it's one of our favourite questions from either the HR or from the nurse educator because they are worried that if they decided to start having children, then it may stall the study. And this is like an intensive kind of study. Like if you really want to have children, you probably have to wait till you finish your internship because if not, then your internship will be affected. So that will be about two and a half years or three years. But there are people who actually still go through during that three years. Like I have seen those bakar school examples as well. So I think it's not possible. I also ever told those who are interested to be in, I say, yes, but I think you have to time it really carefully so that you know when is the time that you can go for having a child. So in this kind of circumstances, then the male nurse won't be affected that much. It's only the female nurses who will get affected because of this childbearing. But I think it's still possible and I think if you time it quite well enough. I think I have one, two, three, four, no, four. Around four of them have sort of like be able to like, let's say, for example, they really need to childbear, right, they would somehow manage to. But there are also some sacrifices that they have to make because they do not take their full four months leave that can be expected to later to take. So considering all that, do you think that females are put at a disadvantage when applying for this in your institution? I guess they would have to consider for themselves their priorities in life. If their priorities in life is family, then probably they may want to do this course later. But then again, as you grow older or your family changes stages, right, you have other issues that may occur later. So to me, I think it's the earlier, if you want to do for master's or master's thesis, the better. Rather than later, but later it's still possible. But it's just that you have to make do with whatever various barriers that come up or obstacles that come your way, you know. You just have to plan it out. You definitely need to have good understanding from your family members, especially your partner, so that there's enough support to allow you to be able to go through the course and do the internship. So when let's say a female candidate comes to the interview and then realises that for the next three years she's not able to do family planning, but she really wants to, maybe she's like late 30s or something and she's worried that she can't have kids later, would it be a hard no for her to enter the course? Okay, so a lot of them, right, when they come for the interview, they seem to have already been formed once. So a lot of them will say, oh I have no intention to have children during this period of time. Yeah, most of them actually are like that. So in the situation that you have raised, where if let's say they really want, then I say, then you have to consider very carefully what is your priorities in life. I think the muscles of nursing won't run away. Maybe if let's say you want to focus on having children at this point of your life, then you may want to focus on family planning, but if you still want to see if you try to do two at the same time, then I can say there are actually successful cases that actually manage to, but really have to plan very well and then let them be the person to decide whether they want to take on that stress. Because they do know that the course itself is actually very, very stressful. The internship is also very stressful. And if you want to add on another stress with regard to having children, then they have to know what is the consequences of their life. There's no hard stop, but we will give the necessary advice according to what we feel is the most working. But we never stop them from having children. I cannot also, this is a national agenda, so we cannot stop them. Then it's really your choice because we can only tell you those examples of how people have made through it. Seems like females have more things to consider when wanting to join the APN workforce. But then I'm just wondering, why is it that men are still not pursuing this track when it seems easier for them to get in? Are there some barriers deterring men from pursuing this track? For the past few years, when I interviewed those who want to apply for SM, I think I have one male, two males out of at least about 13. Every year I get about 6 to 8 candidates to interview. So probably out of the 3 years, maybe 2 out of the 3 years, 3 out of the 3 years, so still about 1 out of 10. In there we only took 1. So the other 2 weren't really suitable for the APN role. But they may be good nurses. So your question, why is it that they are not coming forward for the interview? That's part also I feel, because maybe they deny, reject it. They probably don't want to try and I don't know whether males have their own male community, nurses that they talk about. That's what I'm doing. But I think... Yeah, you can continue first. So I don't know. So they usually will accept the reason why we tell them that they are not suitable for the APN. And then they will look for the next opportunity. They are not the, it feels to me like they are not the die die, must go to APN kind of thing. So for that 2 male nurses that you felt is not suitable, what is it about these 2 in terms of characteristics that make them not suitable? Okay, one, all this will be kept in confidential right? Yeah, don't mention names. So the first one basically found that the APN role is more of like looking at education and research. So we told them you don't need to be an APN to be looking at education and research. Even at this point of time, when you are a nurse, you can look at education and research. So she couldn't articulate what he wants to do in terms of the service that he wants to provide and what can he move towards to in terms of the type of care that he wants to provide for the patient group that he identifies with. So we didn't think it was really that suitable. So we actually encouraged him, if you want to do education and research, continue to do during your nursing career. Like it doesn't need to be an APN. Maybe you want to look for someone who can serve you. Then I think he went to the administrative role. So he did like an award, nurse manager or nurse position role. Then the second one that we didn't take was because he had a lot of certificates. He also has a Master's of Nursing in a particular field. So when we, and he actually requested for a second Master's of Nursing. Then when we asked him, we noticed that he has quite a few credentials. Why does he want to do a Master's of Nursing APN? So when we asked, there wasn't a very clear direction where he wants. It was more of like trying to obtain certificates because I think he felt the need to have academic type of recognition for that. So that's why we also didn't think he was very suitable. So eventually we also rejected him. So these are the two. Not many have come forward that they want to as well. It could be also some reasons of their personal preference of the type of work that they want to do. So just now you mentioned earlier on, you implied that men are less interested in the APN track. Why do you think that they are less interested in this track? So we will again go back to what I have mentioned. Maybe they really prefer like administrative or ethical education or research type of work. Or they haven't really seen themselves in the clinical path they track. Because we know APN is to stop like the inpatient, the outpatient, the dividing service. We need to see this role as something that joust both the medical and nursing. So that they can plan the type of care that is needed. I don't know whether they have that or they want to in terms of that. Or they prefer something that is a bit more structured that they can actually put their talent in. I really don't have the answers for the male. Because they probably think slightly different from how I think. So we won't be able to apply why they do those. But I have also seen very passionate male nurses who want and have a very clear direction of what they want to do after they become APN. So the most recent one which is now enrolled in NUS is actually a very bright boy. And really I think he is very clear about the path he wants to go for. And already he has very good reviews from doctors who have taken them before they come into the Masters of Nursing course. And also my APNs as well. Whether they think this person is capable or not. So far he really has quite good reviews and feedback that he is good to embark on the path of APN. You spoke about structure just now about the career track. So can you expound a bit more about it? Because you guessed that maybe men prefer more structure. That's why they wouldn't choose the APN track. So what is it about this structure that you are implying? We know of all the different pathways. There's administrative pathway, clinical pathway. Clinical pathway itself there's also a few tracks within the clinical. So you can also do clinical as in the nurse clinician role in the ward. Or you can be a nurse clinician specialty in your ward. Then there's just the other part that is the branch of the clinical pathway with the APN role. Then we have the education track and we also have the research track. So for the APN pathway, although it has been since 2006 we had our first APN that graduated. So it was already 15 years back where we wrote our APN and then be able to have a name in terms of the APN. It's a bit more clearer what the APN does. There are still a lot of questions revolving around what is the service that they play. How do they actually cross out that service or that clinic or that inpatient role that they have that differentiate themselves from the nurse clinician in the ward or nurse clinician in the specialty area. It requires a lot of this type of like pioneering type of work to sell your APN to others to tell them what are you actually working at or what are you working for. Whereas the administrative portion of the track is actually much more clear cut. You move up the administrative ladder or track right, you become an NN, become an FNN and then you go up the pathway. It's actually a little bit more clear cut and you want the output of the ward. Then the other role like for example clinical portion. What I meant about the structure would be really, I think it's really very clear in terms of career pathway for the administrative. The clinical portion of the track right, there are also like ranks that they have to move and it's actually very clear those ranks. But there is a certain rank that you are helming the service that you need to start which may let people have second thoughts before they go to that pathway. I also heard of like some male APN who find it also very hard to grow their APN pathway within the institution and they move to other institutions and then they try to create again. Sometimes they have a lot of roadblocks especially if they don't have supportive people who actually guide them along the earlier route. And some actually got lost and then eventually they actually also left the APN. I think that is what I meant when I think it's actually much more clearer and more structured if you decided to go by the administrative pathway or the education of research. But this is my thinking, so I also don't know whether that really applies to all the people. I just find that maybe I'm in the APN pathway so I also realise there's a lot of difficulties that sometimes we have to face. To be able to explain our role to others can be quite hard also even though it's really 15 years down the road. Yes, yes. I mean what I want to gather is your perspective. So don't worry about not having it generalisable to other people. Okay. Yeah, doing very well, doing very well. Very good. Just now you mentioned that when you join the course, you will tell your nurses to be prepared to have their job title or job grade stagnant for 3 years or so. And also their pay and their bonuses may not be as good as their peers that are not in this APN training. Do you think that this would be something that men consider more than women? That's why it deters them from joining this track. Do you think that they consider the money more than women? I don't think we don't explicitly tell them that their PPM, their promotion will be average. But it is a truth that they already know it before it becomes an excuse. I think there may be a possibility that male may have that kind of concept because for them, they need to be a great leader of the family. So they need to consider all the things that I also mentioned. They really need the support from the family. So let's say that is something that they are aware of. For example, their PPM, their promotion may hold till they become this 3 years. Then they may want to take this into consideration whether they want to choose. I think there's a possibility. More so than women. I do hear from females also, ever told me that if they have the priority of family, then they would want to grow their family first and then later come back. So I also interviewed a few females that after they finish their family planning, their children are a little bit bigger, then they come into this. At that point of time, between the age of 25 and 30, is really where they grow their family. I guess it's about the right timing as well. Now moving on to another topic. With regards to gender, I'm just curious to know, do you think that there are gender biases present in the professional development of nurses in the nursing workforce? Because there are so few men, is it easier for nursing leaders to notice men and identify male nurses? Gender bias. My previous PM was a male nurse. So hor, now she's GCM already. Then they will know which is which. Okay maybe we don't talk about general, but what about you? You are also a nursing leader. You as a nursing leader, to be honest, be honest to yourself, when you look at all your nurses, do you feel that you have a tendency to notice a male nurse more than a female nurse? Yes. Definitely there is. So whether you're good or bad, can be both ways also. Can be good or bad. That definitely happens because they are lesser. So you definitely would have noticed them more. If there is a situation where you have two equally competent nurses, one a male and one a female, who would you choose to put up for leadership roles or for promotion or opportunities? I would see the gender. I would really see the capability and competence level rather than gender. Okay, that's good. But generally speaking, do you feel that there are gender biases present in the nursing workforce? Yes. Male, sometimes I prefer male. I also know of more senior female leaders who also prefer male. So, yeah. Okay, very good. So, I'm more interested to know about why there are certain female leaders who prefer males. Let me cite you an example. So for instance, in the corporate world, we don't talk about healthcare and nursing. In the corporate world where it's male-dominated, male of course they tend to choose men. But how come in a female-dominated workforce like ours, our female leaders still tend to choose male and not female? This is a very tough question. Yeah, take your time. I think of putting my mind at those who prefer male nurse. So for you, you're gender equal, right? You don't look at the person by gender. Yeah, I have also a headache for male nurses. So I think, as people, I see male nurses. So I think I wouldn't see them as male or female. But I'd rather speak of them in terms of competency and capability. Okay, so my most senior female nurse leader prefer male. I guess, they seem to be able to relate to the male nurses a little bit more. Yeah, or perhaps the male nurses give them less problems. Or they feel more inclined to a male. I think there could be a few reasons why. Some male nurses are really very obliging. If a sister says something, then they do it quite well. Some of the female nurses will ask a bit more questions. But then male nurses also do ask questions. But I think they tend to be... They do long, they do long. They have less complaints. Like how a female would whine. Maybe male ones whine so much. I guess. Okay, so do you think... Okay, another question now. Do you think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the professional image of nursing in Singapore? Hmm... I wouldn't think so. I actually feel that the capability and competence is important in how they behave professionally. Rather than whether the gender will make a difference with regards to their professionalism. Because females are equally professional if they want to be as well. If we want to look at improving the recruitment of men into the APN workforce, do you have any suggestions on how we can practically do that? For your study, how many male nurses do you interview? It's confidential. Okay. But we try to have a good mix of male and female. How do we increase the number of male nurses into APN? So from what I know, all the male APNs right now really are in mental health. Are they scattered among all the different specialties? Is there a particular discipline that you tend to congregate at? What do you think? I think my classic, the male ones are all from mental health. Those males that I know are all from mental health. Maybe one that is... The one who's only mental health or another hospital. I don't want ICU ones. Because the occupancy is not male, it's all female. So maybe we don't talk about recruitment first. Since you're talking about the specialties, all the male APNs that you know. I know that your institution doesn't really have many male APNs, but if you can think and envision, where do you think male APNs can play a significant role in your institution? Like if you were to have a number, maybe five new APNs that are male, where would you strategically put them in your institution? And you want to take advantage of their gender. I won't take advantage of their gender. Because I really feel... It's not the man or the female that is going to make the difference. I really feel fall back to their competence and capability and what they are very good at. Then they will do that. If they choose to specialize. I will not specifically choose male for specialties. Although we know that in the medical world, I think orthopedics is dominantly by male doctors. We know infection disease is also dominantly by male doctors. I wouldn't. Because I think it's still important that you have the... Still the capability. Now then, let's think about the people that you know, the male APNs that you know who are in mental health, ICU, ED. Why do you think that they are placed in this kind of specialties? Or it's just organically they were just developed from there? The mental health one, because of the need to handle psychiatry patients, I guess. In case they're aggressive type of patients. I think that is why they probably are in mental health. Orthopedic is again, like how the orthopedic surgeons as well, they need to have the strength to hold those big limbs down. So same thing, male APNs and orthopedics probably need to do a lot of skill-based type of work. See the patient's accommodation, like those bones and stuff. So probably that's why the strength is needed. ICU, I think there's really not much of a differentiation. Because I think female or male probably will make such a huge difference in ICU. In terms of quick thinking. Because they are also very good at quick thinking. You know, the person is there. Then are you able to think of any advantages or disadvantages of having male APNs in your institution? Maybe we talk about disadvantages first. Since I think you don't think that male will bring much advantage. You're quite gender neutral. But let's think about, do you think that in the future there will be some issues or there will be some limitations for practice? So the problem would be also the male APN or the male nurse need to see the female patient. So they will definitely need a shut-on. So that is also another additional task. I mean that will be, to call it safe, that will be advantage. If let's say for example we have more male APNs, we will need another additional person to chaperone the person when we do a physical examination. Or maybe some personal HP consultation. Now I think that will be rather worse, female, no matter how you can think of both genders. So that will be probably one of the disadvantages. I think in most of the public centres, there would be a chaperone nurse, like how they chaperone the doctors as well. Do you see an issue about female patients allowing male APNs to do physical examination on them, like how a doctor would? I believe they would still want to ensure that there is a chaperone nurse with them. And even doctors also need that chaperone. So definitely we will still, we will also protect our male nurse or male colleagues that they won't get into any trouble. So definitely we need to make sure that there is a chaperone nurse. But I don't think that the patient will feel anything. So it will work the same way for medical doctor as well. With regards to your up and coming new male APN that is joining your institution, do you foresee he will face any challenges because he is male, apart from the need to be chaperoned? So maybe he can, where will he be practising? Will he be an inpatient or outpatient sort of APN or community type of APN? And would his practice, would his practice or scope of practice be limited because of his gender? He will be inpatient and perhaps also do some outpatient as well. So he is very bright, so I don't think in terms of knowledge wise there will be any issue with regards to him being able to perform that role or able to get through the business or internship. But probably when he comes out to run his service, he will probably need to think through how he is going to see the patient. So if let's say there is a need for a chaperone when he is doing physical examination, then he must make sure that there is someone that will be in the APN. So the only thing about, I know that because we are all moving towards community as well, so there may be some point of time where APNs will not just be inpatient, they may be outpatient, they may also follow through patient into the community. So I think the allocation of patients has to be a little bit more sensitive in terms of, let's say for example if there is a single female patient in the community who does not want to send one male APN to go, but rather another female APN to go. That will be some of the considerations. Then maybe let's go back to the question about recruitment. If we were to, because men seem to be less interested in the APN track, they are more inclined to go and do admin or research or leadership. But then again you see all these three roles like admin, leadership and research also can be encompassed within the APN track. So why is it that men still do not want to be APN? And then how can we overcome that and recruit more men? So you are asking from my point of view about recruiting, I really don't think I need to recruit the male APN for the sake of them being male. I feel in that way. I don't think I need to recruit them for the sake of being recruited. For me, I would rather recruit someone who is good. Rather they will perform their role and they have that inclination to provide the type of work that they will do. Rather than whether they are male or female. So I wouldn't purposefully try to attract male APNs to my group. But not because my group thinks that actually all our female APNs are, then we should remain it as a female. I just feel that if there's a group one, then probably be it male or female, we want them to be part of our family. Don't need to purposefully go and find male to be in our APN family. Actually, before this boy came back to us, I warned my APN family, you got to have a male. So when you are discussing in the WhatsApp chat, please be mindful. Don't talk about ladies' family thing. Then later you all scare him away. But I think these male nurses are also quite open already. They have been in the female-dominating world for the longest time. So I'm sure they will understand. So I really don't think that I need to recruit male nurses because they are male. Yeah, no, I mean that's very wise. It's a very wise way of looking at recruitment. I've covered all the questions, but before I end, I would like you to maybe summarise again your thoughts on why you think that men tend to be less interested in this role. Let me just think of some main points before I can continue. Hang on, give me a while. Okay, I'll pause the recording for a while, okay? Yes, yes. Go on. Okay, so why do we think that why male nurses don't want to choose the career path of the APN? I mean, there could be a few reasons. One main reason could be their own personal needs, depending on their needs. If, let's say, for example, they need to consider their family needs, like for example, we mentioned about them, if they choose the APN pathway, they may not get the promotion, they may not get a performance appraisal that is very high because they are so-called not contributing to the organisation. Then they may consider this because they are probably bringing burdens to their family and living in maybe one different sector. Then, second is about their career pathway. They may prefer to choose a more structured career pathway, like for example, the MS50, or research or education, whereby they are quite much more well-defined in terms of the hierarchy that they need to move up and the work that they need to do. Whereas in the APN career pathway, they tend to be, need to be still searching in regards to the service that they need to be providing for the patient. So, perhaps the structure of the either may be a little bit more appealing to them, so that's why they would rather choose the other pathway, rather than the clinical APN pathway. And lastly would be probably about what they see themselves in terms of being able to go up their career ladder as well. I think some of them may prefer to move up the career ladder and then aspire to be managing people. And maybe the clinical pathway is not what they have ambition themselves to do. So, I think that's about the few points that I have. Okay, thank you. Before I end the recording, do you have any other comments to speak into this conversation that we just had? Okay, I also just summarise my point is that, I think to me there's really no gender differentiation. It is more important of their capability and competency. So, it doesn't matter if they are male or female in the APN. And I feel that the competence and the passion of wanting to be critical is much more important than gender, or bilingual or anything like that. Okay, thank you. I will stop the recording.

segments.text: Do you know of any male APNs in the workforce?
Yes.
Okay, then would you agree that there are very few male APNs in the workforce?
I think it's in comparison with the nursing population.
Like if it's 110, then it will probably be 110 to the nursing population as well for APNs as well.
Okay, maybe let me share some statistics with you.
So, currently in Singapore we have about 11% of the RN population that are men.
But for our APN workforce, only about 5.something% are males.
So why do you think there is such an under-representation of men in the APN workforce?
So, I cannot represent my view for all, but I think somehow male nurses tend to go towards the administrative part of the role.
So maybe that could be one reason why we chose a lesser representative of male nurses that want to be an APN.
Where we know that for APN, they would rather want to pursue on the clinical pathway.
So that could be one reason.
Another reason that I could think of would be administrative.
I'm just thinking about all the male nurses that I have in my hospital.
Either administrative or more towards skilled day type of work.
So they may go into orthopedic perhaps.
And then I think for APN itself, the beneficial ones are actually more so on the medical discipline.
So that could be another second reason.
But I really didn't really ask too many.
But to me, male and female are no different.
But if you are really interested in the clinical pathway and you want to pursue the APN path,
then I think it shouldn't be limited to whether it should be male or female.
As long as you are capable and have that passion to go into clinical pathway, especially like APN.
So you were talking about administrative roles.
What are the administrative roles you are thinking of?
So it would be like nurse manager.
I have quite a few quite bright male nurses who go into more of strategic planning,
planning type of work.
So it's more of those type of work rather than going to the clinical pathway.
Why do you think that men are more inclined to go and do more administrative sort of work
compared to APN kind of work?
I guess it would be their interest, right?
I cannot doubt that there are male nurses who are really very caring as well
and who like to pursue the clinical pathway.
But there are some who are really, in terms of their mind, they are more methodical.
Like more logistically can plan things.
Or even better in writing of corporate complications.
Because I have got a few very talented ones which are really inclined in those rather than...
Or they may even go to research.
But quite a few male nurses who actually chose to do that.
Quite a few compared to female nurses.
So it seems like they are more towards the other pathway.
And I thought all of them are equally as good.
Let's say if they have decided to choose the clinical pathway as well.
In the end, ultimately it goes back to their interest.
What do they want to succeed in within the three pathways?
Administrative, clinical, education and research.
I'm trying to also say that in the clinical track where there is the nurse clinicians and all that.
Men tend not to choose that track as well?
So my male nurse clinicians...
I look after both advanced practitioners and specialty care nurses.
So basically my specialty nurses who are male mainly go into the wound care.
And then they will go to orthopaedic.
So more skill-based work.
For example, maybe they really like the hands-on type of stuff.
Rather than the counselling and education.
Whereas the rest of the education, counselling or other specialty would be held by the female nurses.
I see.
Then do you think that it is important to have more men in the APN workforce?
I think whether it is male or female, it is important.
Must be passionate.
Must be able to endure the APN journey.
And they must have a correct mindset that when they come into APN,
they are into clinical work, service, running like the inpatient or outpatient.
It is not to go into APN because they want to climb up the career ladder.
Like to be promoted or stuff.
So they must really have that passion.
So be it male or female, to me that's the most important thing.
So you don't think that having more men in the APN workforce will make much difference at all?
It's more of the character of the candidate.
I guess there needs to be a good mix.
Because I think there are some ways where guys think a little bit different.
I mean male thinks a little bit different from female.
So I appreciate how you can work together.
It doesn't need to have like...
I think in the workforce itself, I think we appreciate the way how different people think.
And that is how a team is formed.
And I think a team that is formed cannot be of the same character or same personality or the same way of thinking.
Because you will not have change.
You will not have how to improve things.
So I appreciate that there is a good mix of male and female or different type of people.
So what is the difference between men and women that make you think that you will bring a good mix?
Again? Repeat your question please.
What is the difference between male and female nurses that will bring a good mix into the APN workforce?
Because you speak a lot about there is a good mix.
You cannot have people of the same type.
So what is the difference between men and women?
I think men tend... Actually there are also different type of males.
So we have those males who are like body leader type.
Then they would be able to throw ideas, give a plan thing, or write in a way that maybe different from how others may.
But that doesn't discount that some of the females are not able to do so.
So probably it's really...
Perhaps what I appreciate about the male nurses is that
although they are not like the motherly kind of looking after the other nurses,
they can be like the authoritative type that actually also keep their colleagues in check as well.
And making sure that they are looked after.
And if they need to speak up, they may be the ones that speak up for it.
But actually all my male nurses are okay.
Really very good.
We appreciate them for who they are.
But yeah, we really appreciate them for who they are.
But if they want to join APN, I can say my existing nurse function may not want to.
Because they are already in their area of expectation for very very long
and they don't think that they need to go into the APN.
Then that would be their reason why they continue to choose their career path as a nurse clinician.
So specifically to the APN group, I mean your APN colleagues,
I understand that in your institution you don't have any male APNs yet.
So how do you think that having men amongst your APN colleagues would change the dynamics of things?
Okay, so currently I am one from another hospital who is a male APN
who nested to one of my departments, following one of my APNs.
Actually I don't really see a difference whether it is male or female.
I think whatever it is, he just needs to do the necessary work and get all the learning in place
so that he can function as an APN.
I'm really not too sure what other things the male APN can bring to work,
like the career or even my department.
I feel it is not, we shouldn't finger them out because they are male or female.
I think it really depends on whether they have that, in Chinese it's called 听和力,
like they have that commitment, that passion to be able to bring across the APN.
So it doesn't need to be male or female because I've got very good female ones who are able to do so as well.
That's a very good point.
Even during interviews, because what my hospital does is that we have two rounds of interviews
when we are interviewing for APNs to go for the master's program
because the male APN was never one of the factors, but more so their experience.
The clinical experience that they have been working,
what is the intended specialty they are going to specialise in,
actually plays a much important role because if let's say they chose a specialty that perhaps
the hospital doesn't specialise in that they need for that service,
then they may need to switch to other specialty as well.
So it will be based on what the hospital requirements are,
what we think the service is needed so that we will grow the APN with that specialty.
Rather than whether this person is a male or female.
You were talking about the recruitment procedure for your institution,
maybe you can share your experience of being recruited yourself.
How did you first get recruited into the MN program?
During my time, it was less stringent.
When I was first approached by one of my assistant directors, Dan,
she just asked whether I was interested in clinical nursing,
whether I was interested to further my studies,
which I was then very passionate about, rather than doing the administrative role.
The minute they offered the opportunity that I would like to go for it,
I went for it and I just had an interview from the NUS who subsequently got into APN.
Whereas now it is much more stringent, it's much more harder.
It's not about my choice whether the nurse wants to upgrade the studies
and wants to do the part-time work.
But rather, again, like what we mentioned just now,
we look at what are the specialties that this person is interested to be in,
what is the clinical experience of this person,
and then we will ask a series of questions to find out whether this person
actually is suitable for the APN.
Some people may not even come in thinking what the career is going to be like.
So we really want to preempt them to go and find out from other APNs
what is the work that they are going to do in the future,
not just because I am an APN, I can start ordering a doctor around
or I can prescribe medicine or I can tell the doctor what diseases need to be done.
I think it is more than that.
You probably really want to know how to manage a certain group of patients
and you are safe or in fact actually the CUs that have that potential
to want to choose APNs as their career path.
From there, that is about their aptitude, their personality.
Then subsequently, if they pass that round of panel interview,
that panel interview will include APNs like myself,
the HR people and also the nurse education people.
Then we will ask them a few questions
and then we went through this panel interview,
then they will go through another round of, we call it the MMI,
multiple mini interviews where we look into how they critically think in clinical situations,
just like the mini or C but at an S&M level,
so that we see how is their clinical acuteness is like
and how will they respond to those questions.
If they pass through these two, then we will tell them that
okay, then you are selected to go for the Master's of Medicine.
We have to be very, very careful about the way we choose our APNs
because it is like a HDD flag that if you have to back pay,
the bond is like saying don't back pay.
So we must make sure that the person that we choose,
whether it's a male or female, will succeed in this APN pathway.
That will be our financial.
Is there any reason why there is a representative from the nursing education
sitting in the first round of interviews?
So they are the ones who need the sponsorship.
So they will also give feedback about this person,
whether their previous academic requirements.
So we also want to make sure the person that we send can pass the Master's of Medicine.
Let's say for example, this person is more of a field-based or more doing one,
then they should still meet the academic part of the requirement.
So that is where our nurse education colleagues also come in to do some work.
Seems like a lot of things are being covered during the interview
and also the recruitment process and nomination process.
I'm just wondering, do nursing leaders take into consideration the gender of the RN
when nominating him or her for the MN programme?
I don't think so.
I think when the nurse manager or the nurse clinician nominates,
they think probably that the nurses, whether male or female,
perhaps because they want to go into this pathway.
Because they do know that it is a one and a half year course,
another one year internship, then after that it becomes a three year course.
Some may consider all these factors before they put up the application.
I'm sure their ward sisters or brother would have also advised them accordingly
to tell them what do they see them as.
Do they think that they really deserve a foot for the clinical path?
But definitely they won't be able to get all the information from the ward sisters or ward brothers.
Because probably when they come to the panel interview,
we will give them all the information that they need.
During the interview, maybe we talk about your time first, rather than now.
For yourself, when you were being recruited and your nursing leader spoke to you
about entering this course and also to pursue this track,
was there any adjustments that you had to make for your personal life?
Because in terms of family planning, because I understand you're married,
did you have to make some adjustments at that point of time?
At that point of time, I was much younger, I wasn't married yet.
So I just thought, because I was in 7th year of my nursing,
and then they offered me the option of pursuing my Master of Programming,
of course you get that opportunity.
So I think for some, the only probably limiting factor would be,
a lot of times they say if you go for your studies,
your promotion will be held up.
Meaning that because basically to the organisation, you go to school,
you study, you are not actually contributing to the hospital.
And then that is where your, for example, your performance appraisal,
your salary bonus, all this, may be at the normal group rate.
You cannot expect a higher pay or anything like that when you go to study.
And even your promotion may be pulled back later after your internship.
Because during your internship, they will also be near you at your field learning.
So you are not contributing to the hospital, and then they will still not promote you.
But until you reach to the, you pass your APM, you start some service,
and you prove some value from the work that you do,
then they may have promotion.
But otherwise, like personal-wise, because at that point of time,
I think I wasn't into faculty yet, so it doesn't really affect me that much.
But I know of my classmates who are married, and at that point of time,
they may be having children, so it may be tough for them because it's hard.
So the thing that we hear about from our classmates is that,
oh, my children don't recognise me anymore because mummy don't have time
to look after them because they have to study.
So these are probably what my classmates have shared with me.
But I also have quite a lot of classmates that got pregnant and have children.
So I think both ways, I guess.
So that was during your time, quite a number of years ago, right?
But how about now? When you speak with potential candidates,
do you explore this area with them?
Yeah, during the panel interview, it's one of our favourite questions
from either the HR or from the nurse educator because they are worried
that if they decided to start having children, then it may stall the study.
And this is like an intensive kind of study.
Like if you really want to have children, you probably have to wait
till you finish your internship because if not, then your internship will be affected.
So that will be about two and a half years or three years.
But there are people who actually still go through during that three years.
Like I have seen those bakar school examples as well.
So I think it's not possible.
I also ever told those who are interested to be in, I say, yes,
but I think you have to time it really carefully so that you know when is the time
that you can go for having a child.
So in this kind of circumstances, then the male nurse won't be affected that much.
It's only the female nurses who will get affected because of this childbearing.
But I think it's still possible and I think if you time it quite well enough.
I think I have one, two, three, four, no, four.
Around four of them have sort of like be able to like, let's say, for example,
they really need to childbear, right, they would somehow manage to.
But there are also some sacrifices that they have to make
because they do not take their full four months leave
that can be expected to later to take.
So considering all that, do you think that females are put at a disadvantage
when applying for this in your institution?
I guess they would have to consider for themselves their priorities in life.
If their priorities in life is family, then probably they may want to do this course later.
But then again, as you grow older or your family changes stages, right,
you have other issues that may occur later.
So to me, I think it's the earlier, if you want to do for master's or master's thesis, the better.
Rather than later, but later it's still possible.
But it's just that you have to make do with whatever various barriers that come up
or obstacles that come your way, you know.
You just have to plan it out.
You definitely need to have good understanding from your family members,
especially your partner, so that there's enough support to allow you to be able to go through the course and do the internship.
So when let's say a female candidate comes to the interview and then realises that
for the next three years she's not able to do family planning,
but she really wants to, maybe she's like late 30s or something and she's worried that she can't have kids later,
would it be a hard no for her to enter the course?
Okay, so a lot of them, right, when they come for the interview, they seem to have already been formed once.
So a lot of them will say, oh I have no intention to have children during this period of time.
Yeah, most of them actually are like that.
So in the situation that you have raised, where if let's say they really want,
then I say, then you have to consider very carefully what is your priorities in life.
I think the muscles of nursing won't run away.
Maybe if let's say you want to focus on having children at this point of your life,
then you may want to focus on family planning, but if you still want to see if you try to do two at the same time,
then I can say there are actually successful cases that actually manage to,
but really have to plan very well and then let them be the person to decide whether they want to take on that stress.
Because they do know that the course itself is actually very, very stressful.
The internship is also very stressful.
And if you want to add on another stress with regard to having children,
then they have to know what is the consequences of their life.
There's no hard stop, but we will give the necessary advice according to what we feel is the most working.
But we never stop them from having children.
I cannot also, this is a national agenda, so we cannot stop them.
Then it's really your choice because we can only tell you those examples of how people have made through it.
Seems like females have more things to consider when wanting to join the APN workforce.
But then I'm just wondering, why is it that men are still not pursuing this track when it seems easier for them to get in?
Are there some barriers deterring men from pursuing this track?
For the past few years, when I interviewed those who want to apply for SM,
I think I have one male, two males out of at least about 13.
Every year I get about 6 to 8 candidates to interview.
So probably out of the 3 years, maybe 2 out of the 3 years,
3 out of the 3 years, so still about 1 out of 10.
In there we only took 1.
So the other 2 weren't really suitable for the APN role.
But they may be good nurses.
So your question, why is it that they are not coming forward for the interview?
That's part also I feel, because maybe they deny, reject it.
They probably don't want to try and I don't know whether males have their own male community,
nurses that they talk about.
That's what I'm doing.
But I think...
Yeah, you can continue first.
So I don't know.
So they usually will accept the reason why we tell them that they are not suitable for the APN.
And then they will look for the next opportunity.
They are not the, it feels to me like they are not the die die, must go to APN kind of thing.
So for that 2 male nurses that you felt is not suitable,
what is it about these 2 in terms of characteristics that make them not suitable?
Okay, one, all this will be kept in confidential right?
Yeah, don't mention names.
So the first one basically found that the APN role is more of like looking at education and research.
So we told them you don't need to be an APN to be looking at education and research.
Even at this point of time, when you are a nurse, you can look at education and research.
So she couldn't articulate what he wants to do in terms of the service that he wants to provide
and what can he move towards to in terms of the type of care that he wants to provide for the patient group that he identifies with.
So we didn't think it was really that suitable.
So we actually encouraged him, if you want to do education and research, continue to do during your nursing career.
Like it doesn't need to be an APN.
Maybe you want to look for someone who can serve you.
Then I think he went to the administrative role.
So he did like an award, nurse manager or nurse position role.
Then the second one that we didn't take was because he had a lot of certificates.
He also has a Master's of Nursing in a particular field.
So when we, and he actually requested for a second Master's of Nursing.
Then when we asked him, we noticed that he has quite a few credentials.
Why does he want to do a Master's of Nursing APN?
So when we asked, there wasn't a very clear direction where he wants.
It was more of like trying to obtain certificates because I think he felt the need to have academic type of recognition for that.
So that's why we also didn't think he was very suitable.
So eventually we also rejected him.
So these are the two.
Not many have come forward that they want to as well.
It could be also some reasons of their personal preference of the type of work that they want to do.
So just now you mentioned earlier on, you implied that men are less interested in the APN track.
Why do you think that they are less interested in this track?
So we will again go back to what I have mentioned.
Maybe they really prefer like administrative or ethical education or research type of work.
Or they haven't really seen themselves in the clinical path they track.
Because we know APN is to stop like the inpatient, the outpatient, the dividing service.
We need to see this role as something that joust both the medical and nursing.
So that they can plan the type of care that is needed.
I don't know whether they have that or they want to in terms of that.
Or they prefer something that is a bit more structured that they can actually put their talent in.
I really don't have the answers for the male.
Because they probably think slightly different from how I think.
So we won't be able to apply why they do those.
But I have also seen very passionate male nurses who want and have a very clear direction of what they want to do after they become APN.
So the most recent one which is now enrolled in NUS is actually a very bright boy.
And really I think he is very clear about the path he wants to go for.
And already he has very good reviews from doctors who have taken them before they come into the Masters of Nursing course.
And also my APNs as well.
Whether they think this person is capable or not.
So far he really has quite good reviews and feedback that he is good to embark on the path of APN.
You spoke about structure just now about the career track.
So can you expound a bit more about it?
Because you guessed that maybe men prefer more structure.
That's why they wouldn't choose the APN track.
So what is it about this structure that you are implying?
We know of all the different pathways.
There's administrative pathway, clinical pathway.
Clinical pathway itself there's also a few tracks within the clinical.
So you can also do clinical as in the nurse clinician role in the ward.
Or you can be a nurse clinician specialty in your ward.
Then there's just the other part that is the branch of the clinical pathway with the APN role.
Then we have the education track and we also have the research track.
So for the APN pathway, although it has been since 2006 we had our first APN that graduated.
So it was already 15 years back where we wrote our APN and then be able to have a name in terms of the APN.
It's a bit more clearer what the APN does.
There are still a lot of questions revolving around what is the service that they play.
How do they actually cross out that service or that clinic or that inpatient role that they have
that differentiate themselves from the nurse clinician in the ward or nurse clinician in the specialty area.
It requires a lot of this type of like pioneering type of work to sell your APN to others to tell them
what are you actually working at or what are you working for.
Whereas the administrative portion of the track is actually much more clear cut.
You move up the administrative ladder or track right, you become an NN, become an FNN and then you go up the pathway.
It's actually a little bit more clear cut and you want the output of the ward.
Then the other role like for example clinical portion.
What I meant about the structure would be really, I think it's really very clear in terms of career pathway for the administrative.
The clinical portion of the track right, there are also like ranks that they have to move and it's actually very clear those ranks.
But there is a certain rank that you are helming the service that you need to start which may let people have second thoughts
before they go to that pathway.
I also heard of like some male APN who find it also very hard to grow their APN pathway within the institution
and they move to other institutions and then they try to create again.
Sometimes they have a lot of roadblocks especially if they don't have supportive people who actually guide them along the earlier route.
And some actually got lost and then eventually they actually also left the APN.
I think that is what I meant when I think it's actually much more clearer and more structured if you decided to go by the administrative pathway
or the education of research.
